00:04:01.539 --> 00:04:05.899
A question that came in on Slido towards the beginning was,

00:04:05.899 --> 00:04:09.779
is there any other efficient way to code in Python

00:04:09.779 --> 00:04:13.580
without using, this sounds funny to read this question out,

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:15.580
but Python.

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:18.339
So I think it's the way it was written in the Cordo doc,

00:04:18.339 --> 00:04:20.380
but Isabella, do you wanna touch on that?

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:21.339
Yeah, that's right.

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:25.299
So in the webinar, I used a Cordo document

00:04:25.299 --> 00:04:30.299
for the loading of packages, the pulling of the API data,

00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:34.100
the cleaning it up, and then writing it to a PIN.

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:37.059
And I used a Cordo document specifically

00:04:37.059 --> 00:04:42.059
because I had written the API data pull function in Python,

00:04:42.619 --> 00:04:45.260
and I like to clean my data in R,

00:04:45.260 --> 00:04:48.100
and it just did not feel like switching

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:52.859
the code chunk from Python to R itself.

00:04:52.859 --> 00:04:55.100
And so within a Cordo document,

00:04:55.100 --> 00:04:57.859
or if you're familiar with R Markdown documents,

00:04:57.859 --> 00:05:01.179
the executable code is written in these code chunks

00:05:01.179 --> 00:05:02.739
with three backticks,

00:05:02.739 --> 00:05:05.980
and then the name of the language in the curly braces,

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:09.380
then your code, and then ending it with three backticks.

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:12.380
And so anytime in those kinds of documents,

00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:13.619
if you want executable code,

00:05:13.619 --> 00:05:16.019
they have to be within something like that,

00:05:16.019 --> 00:05:20.700
or there's also inline code, but that's slightly different.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:23.260
And so in the example,

00:05:23.260 --> 00:05:26.940
like if I had chosen to do the entire data pull,

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:30.459
say in Python, I could have just used a Python script,

00:05:30.459 --> 00:05:33.779
like .py, and then uploaded that to Connect

00:05:33.779 --> 00:05:35.700
and scheduled it for refreshes,

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:38.459
or similarly, just written everything in R

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:41.500
and uploaded that to Connect in an R script,

00:05:41.500 --> 00:05:44.820
and then rescheduled the refreshes.

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:47.019
The only reason that you see those code chunks

00:05:47.019 --> 00:05:48.100
in a Cordo document

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:50.660
is because I wanted to mix the two languages.

00:05:54.299 --> 00:05:55.579
