00:08:14.779 --> 00:08:19.100
I see Ethan had asked a question that was,

00:08:19.100 --> 00:08:21.959
does PinRead support parquet files?

00:08:23.519 --> 00:08:24.359
Wait, hold on.

00:08:24.359 --> 00:08:27.540
Does PinRead support parquet files, predicate, push down?

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:29.299
Say if I have a big data file,

00:08:29.299 --> 00:08:33.419
but a dashboard only looks at a portion of that file,

00:08:33.419 --> 00:08:36.460
you don't need Shiny to read the whole file.

00:08:40.659 --> 00:08:43.219
Yeah, I can start tackling that one,

00:08:43.219 --> 00:08:46.979
and Isabelle, you can certainly add in any other context,

00:08:46.979 --> 00:08:51.539
but so first off, Pins does support parquet files,

00:08:51.539 --> 00:08:52.380
so that's just something

00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:54.940
we wanna make sure everyone's aware of,

00:08:54.940 --> 00:08:57.419
and parquet files are a fantastic way

00:08:57.419 --> 00:09:02.419
to leverage large data sets very quickly.

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:04.619
Parquet's really awesome.

00:09:04.619 --> 00:09:06.419
Now, if I understand the question correctly,

00:09:06.419 --> 00:09:08.780
it sounds like maybe you have some large data set

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:12.059
that's in a parquet file, potentially pinned somewhere,

00:09:12.059 --> 00:09:14.679
and you only wanna use a portion of that pin

00:09:14.679 --> 00:09:15.520
within your dashboard,

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:18.179
and not necessarily have to read in the entire thing.

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:22.020
So from my understanding,

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:24.460
I don't believe there's a way to read in a pin,

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:26.500
and only read in a subset of it.

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:29.299
For things like that,

00:09:29.299 --> 00:09:31.940
I know we really think of pins as like,

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:35.979
kind of like a minimal, viable data set or object,

00:09:35.979 --> 00:09:38.340
it doesn't have to be just a data set,

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:41.340
that can be easily read and easily shared

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:44.700
across other users and across other pieces of content,

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:46.479
potentially hosted on Connect.

00:09:47.539 --> 00:09:49.900
So we don't really want to think of pins

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:51.780
as more or less like an alternative

00:09:51.780 --> 00:09:53.419
to a database, for example.

00:09:53.419 --> 00:09:55.900
So if you have a very large data set,

00:09:55.900 --> 00:09:58.260
something that's like gigabytes in size,

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:00.700
probably not the best use case for pins,

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:02.700
so we would suggest putting it into a database,

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:06.260
and then the advantage there is that you can actually,

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:10.020
through dplyr, and kind of using dplyr under the hood,

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:12.739
when you go to make a read from that database,

00:10:12.739 --> 00:10:14.219
you don't have to read in the entire thing

00:10:14.219 --> 00:10:15.299
to your Shiny application,

00:10:15.299 --> 00:10:19.059
you can actually only pull in a subset of that data.

00:10:19.059 --> 00:10:21.340
So even it's a really good question,

00:10:21.340 --> 00:10:24.140
I'd probably say it's a little bit more

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:27.239
applicable to databases than actual pins.

