00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:32.080
Okay, one of the questions on Slido earlier was,

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:35.739
how is this better than just accessing data on a server?

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:39.760
Ryan, I think you wanted to take this one.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:42.719
Yeah, it's another really good question,

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:47.239
but I guess my argument would be,

00:11:47.239 --> 00:11:50.479
my data on a server may look very different

00:11:50.479 --> 00:11:51.960
from your data on a server

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:54.599
versus someone else's data on a server.

00:11:54.919 --> 00:11:59.599
It probably depends on, for your specific use case.

00:11:59.599 --> 00:12:03.719
If your data on your server is very clean data,

00:12:03.719 --> 00:12:05.440
it's very easily read in,

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:07.880
it can be easily shared across users,

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:11.679
then maybe just leveraging the data on the server

00:12:11.679 --> 00:12:13.919
could be that solution.

00:12:13.919 --> 00:12:16.479
But if you have a database, like a data warehouse

00:12:16.479 --> 00:12:18.400
where data is kind of dumped in,

00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:21.840
and you want to essentially pull in some of that data,

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:23.479
extract it, clean it,

00:12:23.479 --> 00:12:25.919
make sure it's always being cleaned,

00:12:25.919 --> 00:12:28.599
potentially on a schedule using Posit Connect,

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:32.239
and then load it either back into the database,

00:12:32.239 --> 00:12:34.679
or you can load it as a PIN on Posit Connect

00:12:34.679 --> 00:12:35.919
and make it accessible.

00:12:35.919 --> 00:12:39.359
And that's a really good use case that I see for PINs.

00:12:39.359 --> 00:12:40.200
It's for taking, again,

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:44.599
those kind of minimal chunks of data or some object,

00:12:44.599 --> 00:12:46.200
making sure it's always up to date,

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:50.559
and securely sharing it with whoever using Posit Connect.

00:12:51.559 --> 00:12:53.080
Okay.

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:54.640
I would say for this use case,

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:57.760
just like the Jira board

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:00.719
really does not contain too much information.

00:13:00.719 --> 00:13:01.919
Really what I care about,

00:13:01.919 --> 00:13:03.400
there is versioning on PINs,

00:13:03.400 --> 00:13:05.880
but really what I care about is the most,

00:13:07.039 --> 00:13:10.719
every morning when I check that that is up to date.

00:13:10.719 --> 00:13:14.000
And so it really doesn't need the heavy-dutiness

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.239
of a database schema.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:19.400
And then one other thing I wanted to note

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:21.119
is a nice thing about PINs,

00:13:21.119 --> 00:13:23.239
is that in addition to data,

00:13:23.239 --> 00:13:25.760
it can store other sorts of formats,

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:29.640
so like models, other kinds of R objects as well.

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:32.760
We didn't go too deep into that into this webinar,

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:36.000
but just know there are other kind of use cases

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:37.320
for PINs as well.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:39.159
Highly recommend looking through the website.

00:13:39.159 --> 00:13:40.919
It has really great documentation.

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:43.359
Yeah.

00:13:43.359 --> 00:13:46.359
And I just saw that Jeffrey posted in the chat of really,

00:13:46.359 --> 00:13:48.000
I know a lot of times when I think of PINs,

