00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:21.679
So what guidance can you provide

00:14:21.679 --> 00:14:24.559
regarding small or medium sized data?

00:14:24.559 --> 00:14:26.400
What would be the size of a dataset

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:28.859
for which this demo would not be appropriate?

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:35.119
Yeah, it's a good question.

00:14:35.119 --> 00:14:40.119
And I, so I work like in our solutions engineering team,

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:43.719
and we kind of have this arbitrary threshold

00:14:43.719 --> 00:14:45.400
that we typically tell customers.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:46.960
We say that if your data is getting

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:48.919
on the size of about a gigabyte,

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:51.520
probably not a good idea to put it into a PIN.

00:14:52.559 --> 00:14:55.760
That's not to say a PIN can't handle something larger

00:14:55.760 --> 00:14:57.880
than a gigabyte in size,

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:00.159
just for what PINs was designed to do.

00:15:00.159 --> 00:15:01.919
And a lot of the testing that we've done,

00:15:01.919 --> 00:15:05.640
it's on things that are significantly smaller in size.

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:09.320
So we, again, arbitrary, but we would say a gig,

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:12.039
less than that, probably totally fine for a PIN.

00:15:12.039 --> 00:15:13.479
Once you start getting over a gig,

00:15:13.479 --> 00:15:16.080
you might wanna start exploring some other options.

00:15:20.619 --> 00:15:21.460
